Cell[TextData[{
 "that  ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SubscriptBox["J", "blue"], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    FractionBox["1", "3"], "J"}]}]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.525792369534176*^9, 3.5257924161708508`*^9}}],
 ",  ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SubscriptBox["J", "red"], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    FractionBox["1", "6"], "J"}]}]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.525792369534176*^9, 3.5257924161708508`*^9}}],
 ".  As one advances blue-red-blue from the entry node to the exit node one \
encounters (on the assumption that all resistors have value R) successive \
potential drops ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   FractionBox["1", "3"], "JR"}]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.525792782443572*^9, 3.525792790872615*^9}}],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   FractionBox["1", "6"], "JR"}]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.525792782443572*^9, 3.525792790872615*^9}}],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   FractionBox["1", "3"], "JR"}]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.525792782443572*^9, 3.525792790872615*^9}}],
 ", so if V is the potential difference between the entry/exit nodes we have"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.525792364928897*^9, 3.525792365327052*^9}, {
   3.525792438922166*^9, 3.525792459108322*^9}, 3.525792652318934*^9, {
   3.525792708634861*^9, 3.525792766407976*^9}, {3.525792824231333*^9, 
   3.525792909244779*^9}, {3.525793070093512*^9, 3.525793083725112*^9}, 
   3.5258320502319717`*^9, {3.526219799233863*^9, 3.526219810091261*^9}}],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"                ", 
  RowBox[{"V", "=", 
   RowBox[{
    FractionBox["5", "6"], "R", " ", "J"}]}]}]], "InlineFormula",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.525792914902795*^9, 3.5257929490715*^9}}],

Cell["and the effective resistance of the array becomes", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.525792964275769*^9, 3.525792984342046*^9}, {
  3.525793104836019*^9, 3.525793106098317*^9}}],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"                ", 
  RowBox[{
   SubscriptBox["R", "effective"], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    FractionBox["5", "6"], "R"}]}]}]], "InlineFormula",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.525792991805294*^9, 3.5257930232706823`*^9}}],

Cell["\<\
The simplicity of the argument owes everything to the symmetry of the array, \
and would be lost if (1) we assigned unequal values to the resistors, or (2) \
adopted non-diametric entry/exit nodes. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.525793171361169*^9, 3.525793363452462*^9}, {
  3.5262198788992653`*^9, 3.5262199789248543`*^9}}],

Cell[BoxData["\[IndentingNewLine]"], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{3.525793448919875*^9}]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Introduction to the VARIATIONAL METHOD", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.525802434550613*^9, 3.5258024513048277`*^9}, {
  3.5262200245461817`*^9, 3.526220044200738*^9}}],

Cell[TextData[{
 "It has always seemed to me to be self-evident that current passing through \
a resistive DC network will be so partitioned as to ",
 StyleBox["minimize the dissipation rate",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ". I have never attempted to construct a formal proof of that proposition \
(though have frequently asked students to demonstrate its validity in simple \
cases: two resistors in parallel, the Wheatstone bridge). It is a proposition \
which I have assumed to be well known to electrical engineers, and am \
surprised to discover that as recently as 1999 it was presented in the pages \
of the American Journal of Physics (D. A. Van Baak, \"Variational \
alternatives to Kirchhoff's loop theorem in dc circuits,\" AJP ",
 StyleBox["67",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ", 36 (1999)) as something of a novelty. Van Bank does provide, in his \
Section III, an elaborate \"Proof of the Variational Principle,\" and traces \
its ancestory all the way back to Maxwell, who in ",
 StyleBox["A Treatise on Electricity & Magnetism ",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "\[Section]\[Section] 283-284 proves that\n\n",
 StyleBox["\"In any system of conductors in which there are no internal \
electromotive forces the heat generated by currents distributed in    \
accordance with Ohm's Law is less than if the currents had been distributed \
in any other manner consistent with the actual conditions of supply and \
outflow of the current.\"\n\n",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "Van Baak also cites a comment added by J. J. Thomson as a footnote to \
Maxwell's \[Section]283 when he edited the posthumous ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["2", "nd"], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->"TraditionalForm"],
 " edition of Maxwell's treatisem and \[Section]358 in the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["5", "th"], TraditionalForm]]],
 "edition of J. Jeans' ",
 StyleBox[" The Mathematical Theory of Electricity & Magnetism, ",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "where the subject is revisited.  In the Note which Feynman appended to \
Chapter 19, \"The Principle of Least Action\" (Vol. 2 of ",
 StyleBox["The Feynman Lectures on Physics",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ") he expresses deep interest in the subject\[LongDash]which had only \
recently come to his attention\[LongDash] and in its entropic and unresolved \
quantum mechanical underpinnings. Feynman notes that we have here an instance \
of a variational principle which does ",
 StyleBox["not",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " trace back ultimately to the mechanical principle of least action.\n",
 StyleBox[" ",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "\nHere I am content to accept the validity of that variational principle as \
a given."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.526220178887947*^9, {3.526220214304291*^9, 3.52622023703831*^9}, 
   3.526220287715219*^9, {3.5262203395285254`*^9, 3.526220436650919*^9}, {
   3.52622047219275*^9, 3.526220531755056*^9}, {3.526220566506761*^9, 
   3.526220590488728*^9}, {3.526220723366585*^9, 3.526220750816424*^9}, {
   3.5262207935600033`*^9, 3.52622089318216*^9}}],

Cell[BoxData["\[IndentingNewLine]"], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{3.5262209404118633`*^9}],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Current labeling convention", "Subsubsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.526221354756577*^9, 3.526221360161324*^9}}],

Cell["I will write", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.526221379696917*^9, 3.52622138334396*^9}}],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  SubscriptBox["J", 
   RowBox[{"m", ",", "n"}]], " ", "to", " ", "indicate", " ", "the", " ", 
  "current", " ", 
  RowBox[{"m", " ", "\[LongRightArrow]", " ", "n"}]}]], "DisplayFormula",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.5262213905908318`*^9, 3.52622144530422*^9}}],

Cell["as indicated in the following figure:", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.526221493404277*^9, 3.5262215034087973`*^9}}],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"GraphPlot", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"m", "\[Rule]", 
      SubscriptBox["n", "1"]}], ",", 
     RowBox[{"m", "\[Rule]", 
      SubscriptBox["n", "2"]}], ",", 
     RowBox[{"m", "\[Rule]", 
      SubscriptBox["n", "3"]}]}], "}"}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{"VertexLabeling", "\[Rule]", "True"}], ",", 
   RowBox[{"DirectedEdges", "\[Rule]", "True"}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.526221194389183*^9, 3.5262212640123043`*^9}, 
   3.5262212970095*^9}],

